They would intermittently cross the state line for the next few minutes before moving deeply into AZ. In the time spent in New Mexico, both birds allowed fairly close photos and prolonged looks of their silver wingtips, black heads when in good light, short tails, and broad wings.

Observation Details: We didn't try to count the vultures.  They were very active and we were busy taking photos.  I am guessing at least 50 Black Vultures were in the mix, outnumbering the Turkey Vultures noted.  //  In the photos below, there are three pictures that tickled us.  Photo #4 captures the near collision of two vultures, a single feather floating down to earth.  This scene comes with a short conversation, I feel sure.  It goes something along the lines of "Oops.  Excuse me.  Coming through."  Photo #5 shows two vultures so closely aligned it looks like one bird has two sets of legs.  Photo #6 follows a Black Vulture being harassed by a Great-tailed Grackle.  The smaller bird would not leave the vulture alone; it chased it around and around and even stalked it once the vulture landed on a rooftop.

Incredible first NWT record!  Locals say it's been here for nearly a month. Posted on Facebook and I chose to come see it during my long weekend. Not banded or otherwise marked bird.  Bird frequently flies around town, perching up on poles in backyards, with bouts of soaring. Otherwise near dump in poplar trees or on refuse. Flight noted to be quick bursts of furious flapping interspersed with soaring. Active wing moult as typical in summer vultures.

Reported and photographed by Casey Hynes at dusk last night; then found by Doug Hitchcox and Josh Fecteau this morning. Don Mairs and I arrived in the area and first tried looking on the river side of town along 3rd Street. We had gone no further than the first corner when we saw the bird sitting on a rooftop.  Stocky vulture with heavy neck ruff, black and wrinkled skin on head, dark gray legs and feet, all black body that was short at the rear. I could see white primary shafts on the outer primaries. The bill had a paler, hooked nail. The bird flew down to drink from ice melt at the edge of a driveway. I noted the white in the outer wings and short, squared tail. The bird sat on its tarsi to dip down and drink. The left eye appeared damaged, and the bird acted skittish to that side, sometimes wheeling around to its right (good eye side) to see what was "around the other side." Quite comical in motion. After drinking, the bird flew on its own up to a tall conifer, where it perched mid to lower-mid height.  It is possible this is the same Black Vulture seen by Fyn Kynd in Searsmont (27-28 May this year: https://ebird.org/ebird/me/view/checklist/S29947946). That bird held its left eye closed similar to what I saw on the Farmingdale bird. With the eyelid open, the Farmingdale bird showed the damage to the eye itself. But Fyn points out that his bird perhaps had the left eye missing entirely, showing a more sunken socket. Odd coincidence if so.

Observation Details: Birds were very hard to count, as some were in air (getting away from me) and many others were perched at spread out locations in this area.  This stop started with only a single Turkey Vulture, which by itself was unexpected.  Next, I saw a kettle of 12 Turkey Vultures, then another kettle of 20+ vultures that included 3-5 Black Vultures.  I tried to get closer to get photos of the Black Vultures, only to notice multiple Black Vultures perched in trees, etc, around area.  While trying to count, had a lady walk out and yell "kill 'em all - those damn things".  I asked her if they are here regularly, she explained yes and that they S**T all over everything.   I then drove up road to the cemetery (public), house nearby has multiple feeders, likely a lot more species/birds present than this list indicates.    This location is about 30 miles west of Klondike Park, so very possible this is part of the population seen there.

The long-time Marin-resident BLVU has been hanging out around Bolinas Lagoon for the past month or so. Based on reports I knew it roosts in the eucs just north of the school on Olema-Bolinas Rd. After missing this bird earlier in the day I decided to come back and stake-out the spot in the late afternoon, hoping I could see the bird as it came in. After an hour wait here, at least two dozen vultures started to stream in to their eucalyptus roost around 3:30pm. Near the group, but not always with them, the BLVU appeared from the south. For the next 20 minutes it flew around the area, and made multiple passes directly overhead. Last seen flying off to the north. Smaller than the TUVUs, with broader, flatter black wings, and silver primaries. Black head, very short, almost triangular tail. Due to wind it was soaring much of the time, but occasionally it would flap its wings with quicker, snappier wingbeats than the TUVUs, more like a hawk. Easy to pick out of the TUVUs by these features even with the naked eye. Many photos to be posted. Lifer!

Incredible first NWT record!  Locals say it's been here for nearly a month. Posted on Facebook and I chose to come see it during my long weekend. Not banded or otherwise marked bird.  Bird frequently flies around town, perching up on poles in backyards, with bouts of soaring. Otherwise near dump in poplar trees or on refuse. Flight noted to be quick bursts of furious flapping interspersed with soaring. Active wing moult as typical in summer vultures.

Just after the rain let up, we found him hanging out with a group of Turkey Vultures that seemed to have perched on snags of a dying tree to get out of the rain. We thought he was going to be an immature Turkey Vulture, but discovered he was indeed a Black Vulture.  After we arrived, the Turkey Vultures all flew, but he seemed reluctant to fly off and appeared to want to sun himself, albeit awkwardly, almost like a first year.

Observation Details: Glanced out my door in time to see a nervous CORA in low avoidance flight looking above it while a AMCR was aggressively calling loudly out of sight. I knew a large predator was likely in the area. I looked higher to see a large dark bird turning (which I was half expecting to be a GOEA), suddenly broke from its soar flapping right toward my house which I instantly recognized as a BLVU!! I immediately ran for my camera, emerging in total panic actually spooking the BLVU (now almost right over my yard) being closely dogged by the aggressive AMRC. Both turned and flew south while being buffeted eastwards by strong gusting WNW winds. The bird crow gave up pursuit, and the BLVU crossed the Rideau River and I soon lost sight of it without bins.

Don and I were remarking about the low quantity's of species at Diekman's this year. We saw a couple turkey Vultures and he turned to me and said, "Turkey Vultures, Why don't we see that Black Vulture here?" 5 seconds later the Black Vulture flew in front of us with a gull harassing it. It landed on the house just south of the parking lot with the other TVs. I think you could have pushed us over with a feather. Unbeknownst to us, Rick Lebaudoour had found it down at Porto Bodega and was yelling at us from there to see it, but we didn't hear him, when it flushed from his location. He joined us very soon thereafter and more folks were able to see it too. Many very good photos of this bird. It flew from the house to several locations nearby. Quicker wingbeats and little soaring compared to TVs nearby. Landed often and not too far away as an average. Finally relocated to Porto Bodega to see it again before it flew off to the north.

Don and I were remarking about the low quantity's of species at Diekman's this year. We saw a couple turkey Vultures and he turned to me and said, "Turkey Vultures, Why don't we see that Black Vulture here?" 5 seconds later the Black Vulture flew in front of us with a gull harassing it. It landed on the house just south of the parking lot with the other TVs. I think you could have pushed us over with a feather. Unbeknownst to us, Rick Lebaudoour had found it down at Porto Bodega and was yelling at us from there to see it, but we didn't hear him, when it flushed from his location. He joined us very soon thereafter and more folks were able to see it too. Many very good photos of this bird. It flew from the house to several locations nearby. Quicker wingbeats and little soaring compared to TVs nearby. Landed often and not too far away as an average. Finally relocated to Porto Bodega to see it again before it flew off to the north.

I scanned all with a scope and found exactly one turkey vulture among the perched birds. One of the BLVU was tagged 74A.  A number of vultures flew into the vegetation where I couldn’t see them. These are not included in the count.

Observation Details: Nous sommes retourné tôt ce matin pour voir si l'urubu noir trouvé hier était encore présent. À notre arrivée, il était immobile sur un rocher au sol près de la carcasse de baleine où se nourrissaient plusieurs goélands marins. L'oiseau s'est avéré très peu craintif, en fait il m'a à toute fin pratique ignoré tout au long de l'observation. Il a même décidé de se coucher sur la roche, sans même s'éloigner. J'ai pu mieux voir son œil gauche en agrandissant une photo et il semble effectivement avoir une anomalie, comme s'il n'avait pas de pupille (voir photo). À mon départ, il était toujours couché sur la même roche.

Found by Julie Ray and reported to Nel Hecht who called Chris Howard, my husband, who told me!   How’s that for a telephone line. I notified Jon Dunn who lives close by and met him at the ranch where the bird had been photographed earlier that morning at 7:40 AM. The bird was on private property but could be seen from the Pine Creek Road if you looked hard. The owner came out and invited us onto the property where we got close looks and photographed. We believe it to be the same bird that was here last year at the exact same time for the Bishop Christmas Bird Count. Last year‘s bird had an injured left eye as does this bird. There is a dead calf nearby in the field and the owner feels this is what attracted the Black Vulture to this area.  Amazing that this bird has returned to spend the winter or at least a portion of it here in Bishop once again. I cried. Entirely black vulture with shriveled grayish facial skin. Right eye looks normal and slightly reddish and left eye is closed shut with shriveled skin all around it. Very long pale gray hooked bill. Extensive white base on outer primaries. Long bare gray legs.
Presumed to be the same bird from this time last year as it has an injured left eye.  Black with white wing-tips and a gray, wrinkly head.

Observation Details: Both seen together at 12:20 pm flying in thermals while hawkwatching from here on BLM land: (31.34893, -109.04913). The birds initially coasted from the SE of us from NM and tracked towards AZ, following the ridge directly south of us (31.3466300, -109.0479800). They would intermittently cross the state line for the next few minutes before moving deeply into AZ. In the time spent in New Mexico, both birds allowed fairly close photos and prolonged looks of their silver wingtips, black heads when in good light, short tails, and broad wings.

Observation Details: Incredible first NWT record!  Locals say it's been here for nearly a month. Posted on Facebook and I chose to come see it during my long weekend. Not banded or otherwise marked bird.  Bird frequently flies around town, perching up on poles in backyards, with bouts of soaring. Otherwise near dump in poplar trees or on refuse. Flight noted to be quick bursts of furious flapping interspersed with soaring. Active wing moult as typical in summer vultures.

After an hour-long drive all around El Faro, I finally found this bird, which had been reported by local birders for the last couple of weeks. This continuing bird was perched on top of a tool shed or shack in the backyard of a local home. It was quietly standing on top of the metal roof, as shown in the attached photo. I suspect the house's owner may be feeding the bird, and that is why it has stuck around the neighborhood for so long, and not flown away. Note: The house with the backyard shack  is the fifth or sixth house found on the left side of the road before reaching the muddy edges and dirt road at the southern tip of the lagoon. It is a wooden house, painted orange and with the window frames painted blue.

Observation Details: I arrived at nearly the same time as Evan Lipton, and the two of us watched the birds until they left the roost at 8:14 AM. There were initially 3 TUVU and 2 BLVU sitting close together right at the edge of the pond; until a 4th TUVU dropped in from the south, and the birds starting getting jumpy. The blacks bullied the TUVU off the prime perch in a snag at the edge of the pond, forcing the TUVU to pair up and scatter into the surrounding trees. At about 7:00 AM, the blacks moved from the snag to a dense tangle at the southern edge of the pond, and at 8:14 AM, all 6 vultures put up nearly simultaneously, quickly circled up to a significant altitude, and drifted away into Dedham, right over Great Blue Hill and Fowl Meadow.

Observation Details: I located this roost just before sunset last night, and counted 6 vultures. One bird appeared to have a black head and an all black, not brown body, but it was situated lower on the roost, and partially blocked from view. I was nearly certain that it was a Black Vulture at that time, but was being cautious to avoid making a misidentification due to the failing light, or being lured into the trap of confirmation bias. Most of the other birds present were easily identified as Turkey Vultures, with their bare, red heads and dark brown bodies, but some were partially blocked from view at times. Since I couldn't identify the entire group with complete certainty, I decided to return to the roost early this morning, and try and have another look.   Taran arrived before I did this morning, and had already located and identified one of the Black Vultures. We both observed the entire group while it was still on the roost, and determined that there were six in total, and that most of them were Turkey Vultures. The birds eventually began lifting off and flying away, one by one. This was a great help to us, and they were all easily identified in flight. The two Black Vultures had bare, black heads, black bodies, and silvery wingtips clearly visible as they flew off.

Observation Details: Chance encounter while raking leaves in the yard. Large black raptor that immediately stood apart from a TUVU due to proportions (short square tail, short neck and small head) and flight style (wings held almost flat with quick shallow wingbeats followed by glides). Merlin describes flight as bat like, which is a great description.  Otherwise almost entirely black except for silvery underside of primaries. Silvery legs were also conspicuous against black tail.  One other noteworthy observation: watched a RTHA go after the BLVU which I've never seen happen to a TUVU.

Observation Details: Big surprise as I was driving down the road and saw a couple of these raptors fly south over Lake Road as I was driving west. Initially assumed Turkey Vulture, but they were more “flappy” (quicker, batlike wingbeats) and shorter tail obvious so I quickly switched gears to Black Vulture and pulled over to get a better look and saw the silvery wingtips. Was able to grab some quick shots to show the group of five and some more detailed, zoomed in shots of some individuals before they disappeared going southwest from the intersection. Far from the known in roost in Lewiston, so likely migrants.

Observation Details: Nous sommes retourné tôt ce matin pour voir si l'urubu noir trouvé hier était encore présent. À notre arrivée, il était immobile sur un rocher au sol près de la carcasse de baleine où se nourrissaient plusieurs goélands marins. L'oiseau s'est avéré très peu craintif, en fait il m'a à toute fin pratique ignoré tout au long de l'observation. Il a même décidé de se coucher sur la roche, sans même s'éloigner. J'ai pu mieux voir son œil gauche en agrandissant une photo et il semble effectivement avoir une anomalie, comme s'il n'avait pas de pupille (voir photo). À mon départ, il était toujours couché sur la même roche.
